all, so OK, but the relative-join semantics now depend on payload cwd, which is undocumented.\nFix: canonicalize once in `prepare_transcript`; drop the `cli.rs:339-343` join or document it. (P2)\n\n**Side effects before cheap validation — association target validated, but storage dir created earlier via lock (P1)**\nOrder in `record_agent_log`: `resolve_workdir` → `resolve_association_target` (read-only resolve, good, validates early per the test at `cli.rs:992`) → `prepare_transcript` (reads/parses transcript) → `with_capture_lock`. But `with_capture_lock`→`capture_lock_path` (`capture_lock.rs:32`) does `create_dir_all(storage_path)` — a filesystem side effect — and this is the *first* thing inside the lock, before any further validation. More notably, `prepare_transcript` does full file read + JSON parse of the entire transcript *before* the lock and before any GitMeta state is consulted; that's fine for correctness but the parse can `bail` (`transcript.rs:43`) after `resolve_association_target` already succeeded — error ordering is parse-fails-last, which is acceptable. No P1 correctness break here; downgrade.\n\n**`agent.context(\"agent is required\")` checked after stdin read (P2)**\nHook path (`cli.rs:208-211`) reads all of stdin, parses JSON (`run_hook`/`cli.rs:288`), filters transcript_path, *then* checks `agent` at `cli.rs:301`. A missing-agent invocation does I/O + JSON parse before the cheap required-arg check.\nFix: move `agent.context(...)?` to top of `run_hook`. (P2)\n\n**Two source-of-truth facts for dedup: `record-hashes` set vs per-turn detail records (P2)**\nDedup uses the `record-hashes` Set (`write.rs:69-84`) to drop seen records. Separately, `enrich_incomplete_turn` re-derives \"is this the same turn\" by matching `detail[\"records\"]` hashes against incoming (`write.rs:491`). When *all* incoming records are already seen, records empties (`write.rs:86`) and enrichment matches by record hashes — but the `record-hashes` set already proved they're dupes, while the turn-detail match is a second, independently-stored copy of the same membership fact. If the two diverge (e.g. a turn detail written but record-hashes set edit lost), dedup and enrichment disagree silently. They're meant to be the same truth.\nFix: derive enrichment-match from the turn detail consistently, or document that record-hashes is authoritative. (document-only)\n\n**Capture-lock scope: previous-turn read is correctly inside the lock (OK)**\n`latest_stored_turn` (`write.rs:60-63`) and the `record-hashes` read (`write.rs:69`) both run inside `write_transcript_batch`, which runs inside `with_capture_lock` (`cli.rs:358`). Good — read-modify-write is atomic under the lock. However `resolve_association_target` (`cli.rs:347`) runs *outside* the lock, opening a Session and resolving the target before lock acquisition; the target could be invalidated by a concurrent writer between resolve and `associate_session` (which re-resolves inside the lock at `write.rs:237`). The re-resolve inside makes this safe but means the outer resolve is purely a pre-validation that's then thrown away and redone. Two resolves of the same target.\nFix: pass the resolved target into the lock body, or rely solely on the inner resolve plus an early cheap parse check. (P2)\n\n**`entry_timestamp` monotonic-bump fights `Utc::now()` (P2)**\n`write.rs:111-114`: `now` for transcript entries, then `entry_timestamp = now.max(prev.timestamp+1)`; separately `updated_at`/turn-summary timestamp (`write.rs:146`, `:169`) calls `Utc::now()` *again* and also `entry_timestamp + records_captured`. Three timestamp notions (wall-clock millis for transcript, bumped sequence for ordering, fresh rfc3339 for updated-at) that are supposed to represent \"when this turn was captured.\" The summary `captured_at` (rfc3339) and the summary list-entry timestamp (`entry_timestamp + records_captured`) can disagree with each other under clock skew/bump.\nFix: compute `now` once, derive all three from it. (P2)\n\n**`source_identity` lossy on non-session-id transcripts (P2)**\n`capture.rs:46-50`: when no `session_id`, `session_key` is hashed from `source_path.as_os_str().as_encoded_bytes()` — the *canonical* path. `source_key` is always the canonical path. So for session-id-less transcripts, moving/renaming the file yields a brand-new session (path-derived identity), silently fragmenting one session into many. Path becomes lossy session identity.\nFix: document that session-id-less agents key on path; or fall back to a stable in-file marker. (document-only)\n\n**Minor: `non_empty_path`/`non_empty_value` only guard empty, not whitespace (P2)** — `cli.rs:393`, `:401`. A `\" \"` transcript path passes, then fails later at canonicalize with a less direct error.\n\nNo P1 correctness defects found; the lock scope and dedup read placement are correct. Top actionable items: collapse repeated repo discovery/Session opens (P2, biggest waste), single timestamp source (P2), early agent-check in hook (P2)."}],"totalDurationMs":44846,"totalTokens":81157,"totalToolUseCount":9,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":61234,"cache_read_input_tokens":17520,"output_tokens":2401,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":61234},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":2401,"cache_read_input_tokens":17520,"cache_creation_input_tokens":61234,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":61234,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":9,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":0,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":0}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"[REDACTED:entropy]","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-desktop","cwd":"[REDACTED:entropy]","sessionId":"[REDACTED:entropy]","version":"2.1.142","gitBranch":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}